snippet:
Dropped by here with two of my friends after a casual walk around Georgetown.

Indian food is always good. Herbivore serves the best one by far. It is for those looking for high quality, colorful, tasteful Indian food for takeout or eating on-location.

Definitely for those (group or individual) looking for good food and a place to talk. Its peaceful, air conditioned, colorful setting is a delight to spend time in.

Parking can be a hassle but we were lucky to find one 5 houses up.

Would definitely recommend.

snippet:
Honestly we were a bit disappointed.  A few pet peeves first.  The fact that everything is disposable is annoying especially with the tiny water cups that you get one sip out of.  We also heard someone get some meat options which, unless they were vegan meat, means herbivore is not vegiterian.  That's fine if your not pretending to be but that could be pretty bad.

The food itself was just okay.  The spices were decent but it was a bit dry and didn't have the texture we like.  The atmosphere was nothing special but there is window seating that looks out on the town which is nice.  It is set up in almost a fast food style where you get the food yourself, and toss the trash in the bin when your done.

snippet: Recently had the pleasure of dining at an exceptional Indian restaurant in Georgetown, D.C. The restaurant's warm and inviting atmosphere immediately made me feel at home. I was recommend the restaurant from a clothing store close by. The staff were friendly, attentive, and knowledgeable, helping me navigate the extensive menu. The food was outstanding, with dishes like samosas, dal makhani, lamb rogan josh, butter chicken, garlic butter naan and chai tea, showcasing the chef's skill and attention to detail. The prices were very reasonable, especially considering the generous portion sizes. Overall, I highly recommend this restaurant to anyone seeking an authentic and delicious Indian dining experience in Georgetown D.C.

response.snippet: Jasmine, we apologize for the inconvenience. However, you were informed prior to your order that we use the same oil for frying meat and vegetarian options so you could order something non-fried assuming you are a pure vegetarian. But your order had a Chicken dish, so we don’t see how that was an issue to you since you do consume meat. The aloo paratha is a side itself as mentioned in the menu so it would not come with a side. Meat items cannot be precooked as it would not be edible. The kitchen is an employee-only area so it’s a false claim that it is unhygienic. We appreciate the feedback but won’t be accepting any false claims. Thank you!

snippet:
Stumbled upon Herbivore Indian Cuisine during a DC visit and really liked the overall experience. Simple, tasty, and satisfying.

Some quick notes:

* Small but cozy restaurant with a welcoming vibe
* Food was good and had that touch of homemade flavor
* Both vegetarian and non-vegetarian options available
* Portion size was on the smaller side but filling and flavorful
* Naan was fresh and soft—definitely a highlight
* Quick service and polite staff
* Clean interiors and neatly maintained space
* Roadside parking available nearby, typical for DC
* Great spot for a casual meal with authentic Indian taste

Chicken seekh kabab was ok, not that good, as lack of spices and too much of bellpeppers and grill onions on side.

How can you get wrong on chutneys.
Rest its worth a try.Sunday parking is free in DC which will save you lot of time finding a spot.

snippet:
I visited Herbivore thinking it was a vegetarian restaurant—as the name strongly implies—but to my surprise, there were non-vegetarian items on the menu. That felt misleading and completely defeats the point of calling the place “Herbivore.”

I ordered the vegetarian biryani, which turned out to be nothing more than a blend veg pulao

To top it off, they added a 10% service fee to our bill—even though it was just the two of us dining. No one told us about it in advance, and there was no mention of it on the menu or anywhere visible. That lack of transparency was frustrating and felt sneaky.

Overall, the experience was a letdown—poor food, misleading name, and hidden charges. I wouldn’t recommend this place, and I won’t be returning.

I ordered the vegetarian biryani, which turned out to be nothing more than a blend veg pulao

To top it off, they added a 10% service fee to our bill—even though it was just the two of us dining. No one told us about it in advance, and there was no mention of it on the menu or anywhere visible. That lack of transparency was frustrating and felt sneaky.

Overall, the experience was a letdown—poor food, misleading name, and hidden charges. I wouldn’t recommend this place, and I won’t be returning.

snippet: The name herbivore and the rating of 4.8 stars stood out to me, as my family is health conscious. However, we felt disappointed by the food quality and overall experience. The restaurant is small and well patronized, and the staff was friendly, but the food was overpriced, plus you must pay at the counter and tip in advance. The food was prepared quickly but served on paper plates with plastic cutlery and cups. The food did not taste like it was prepared with fresh ingredients but primarily pre-packaged and/or frozen ingredients. I would expect lower prices or higher quality food.
